\begin_layout Standard
The way I learned (and still think about) Clifford algebras is in terms of a symmetric bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and orthonormal finite–dimensional basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle e_{i},e_{j}\right\rangle =\eta_{ij}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{ij}=\pm\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 is diagonal with some signature.
 The Ansatz appears to be this.
 First,
 write 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle e_{i},e_{j}\right\rangle +\left\langle e_{j},e_{i}\right\rangle =2\eta_{ij}$
\end_inset

 which is an entirely reasonable things to do,
 and then ask 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

is there an algebraically similar representation that is expressed in matrix form?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 that is,
 where we take the 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 not to be vectors,
 but matrices,
 and replace the bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 by matrix multiplication.
 This requires a slight abuse of notation,
 so as to write 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}\gamma_{j}+\gamma_{j}\gamma_{i}=2\boldsymbol{1}\eta_{ij}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset

 is the identity matrix having the same 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 size as the size of the matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 So what is this,
 exactly?
 A slight–of–hand?
 We say,
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

oh,
 a haha,
 here is an algebraic expression,
 having this symbological form.
 What other symbolic expressions have the same form,
 but whose symbols have different semantic interpretations?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 There are at least three maybe four answers to this question.
 The narrowest,
 in the current context,
 is representation theory:
 representing algebraic relationships with matrices.
 Slightly broader is the representation of algebraic relationships with actions on sets.
 If these are plain sets,
 these are set–theoretical sets,
 and that's that.
 If these sets also have additional structure,
 e.g.
 are perhaps (infinite–dimensional) topological vector spaces,
 or if these sets are families of differentiable curves,
 then we can ask about the representation of that algebraic expression subject to additional axiomatic constraints imposed on these symbols.
 To make this conversation less abstract,
 and illustrate it with a specific example:
 I can ask:
 are there any representations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}\gamma_{j}+\gamma_{j}\gamma_{i}=2\boldsymbol{1}\eta_{ij}$
\end_inset

 where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}$
\end_inset

 are operators acting on a set,
 or where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}$
\end_inset

 are operators acting on a family of differentiable curves?
 How about representations where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}$
\end_inset

 are operators acting on Riemann surfaces?
 On elliptic curves?
 What about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

–adic representations?
 And so on.
\end_layout

