information
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 has something to do with an electron being in a bound state with a proton,
 and furthermore,
 that picture of a bound state must necessarily be accompanied by the emitted photon(s),
 which are busy running away at light–speed.
 Is this an adequate model for how transistors record information?
 Certainly,
 it is true that as electrons flow down the wires,
 there are induced electromagnetic fields that bop around and are then promptly absorbed by other nearby wires,
 or kind of anything nearby,
 including the computer case itself.
 At this point,
 they contribute to the noise floor,
 although this is swamped by thermal noise.
 This complex set of interactions allows for a stable state to be achieved and held for extended periods of time;
 that stable state encodes information.
 Whatever that is.
